				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1404533&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204975" alt="Zyn" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1404533)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;" >Zyn</a></span> <span class="odate time_1486169523 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">04 Feb 2017 00:52</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2739949">
									

<p>Researching obscure topics can be hard sometimes. Sometimes we can just use the information on Wikipedia articles or science sites pulled from Google. Some people, like Randall Munroe of <a href="https://what-if.xkcd.com/">What if? and xkcd</a>, will search up peer-reviewed articles published in professional journals to learn more about certain aspects of science.</p>
<p>The SCP wiki has the <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/expert-witnesses">Expert Witnesses page</a> listing site members who have professional and/or academic knowledge on topics they can advise on. That's usually a good place to start if you have something that the internet isn't being straightforward or niche-detailed enough with.</p>
<p>This thread is for everyone to share interesting/useful scientific resources they use when writing (ideally, .org/.gov/.edu things?). Also for people to show things they looked at a lot that inspired them to write something else. Case in point, reading a picture book version of <em>The Tale of Genji</em> wall paintings totally counts as research if you use the knowledge to construct a fictional court of noblemantids with secret illegal dueling rings.</p>

							</div>

								
					
