															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=455145&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204975" alt="Petrograd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=455145)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;" >Petrograd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1486663296 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 Feb 2017 18:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2743799">
									

<p>This is porting over advice we give undergrads and shaving off the stuff you may not have access to, so the focus is a bit different, but just general research advice:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>If you're trying to research something you're not familiar with, Google and Wikipedia are good places to start. Often the trouble is not knowing the correct technical terms, which can be pretty opaque. Do not give up. Try different combinations of words and synonyms. Start on Wikipedia pages for terms you <em>are</em> familiar with and follow the links.</p>
<p>If a Wikipedia summary doesn't go far enough and you're googling for more detail, .edu or .gov links are more likely to get you something reliable than just clicking whatever.</p>
<p><a href="https://scholar.google.com">Google Scholar</a> is the next step if you actually want to start digging for academic papers or references. (It's probably overkill for anything on the wiki, but the tool's there if you need it.) It's a crapshoot, but it's a lot more forgiving as a search engine than professional/academic databases.</p>
<p>Also, if you go to a university, you're almost guaranteed to have access to databases and research librarians. Research librarians get bored and are paid to help you find any damn thing you please. (Hell, public librarians might too.) If they ask you can tell them it's for creative writing. Or tell them about SCP. Whatever. I've used library resources for the dumbest shit in the past.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

